2026-06-27 | Tiling a Floor With 1 × M Tiles

	Question
Return the number of possible tilings modulo 10^9+7.
	Key Insight
Let:
		dp[i]
	be the number of ways to tile a floor having:
		i rows
		and m columns
	Consider the last row(s).
	Case 1: Place the last tile horizontally
	A horizontal tile covers the entire last row.
	So the remaining floor has:
		i - 1 rows
	Ways:
		dp[i-1]
	Case 2: Place tiles vertically
	A vertical tile occupies:
		m consecutive rows
	To fill the last m rows, we need one vertical tile in every column.
	So the remaining floor has:
		i - m rows
	Ways:
		dp[i-m]
	Recurrence
	If i < m:
		dp[i] = 1
	(only horizontal placement is possible)
	If i == m:
		dp[i] = 2
	(all horizontal or all vertical)
	If i > m:
		dp[i] =
		dp[i-1] + dp[i-m]
	Approach
1.	Create a DP array of size n+1.
2.	Base cases:
			dp[0] = 1
			for i < m:
				dp[i] = 1
			dp[m] = 2
3.	For every i > m:
			dp[i] =
			dp[i-1] + dp[i-m]
4.	Return dp[n].
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int tileFloor(int n, int m) {
        const int MOD = 1000000007;
        vector<long long> dp(n + 1, 0);
        dp[0] = 1;
        for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if(i < m)
                dp[i] = 1;
            else if(i == m)
                dp[i] = 2;
            else
                dp[i] = (dp[i - 1] + dp[i - m]) % MOD;
        }
        return dp[n];
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		n = 7
		m = 4
	DP values:
		dp[0] = 1
		dp[1] = 1
		dp[2] = 1
		dp[3] = 1
		dp[4] = 2
		dp[5] = 3
		dp[6] = 4
		dp[7] = 5
	Output:
		5
	Key Insight
	At the end of the floor, there are only two possibilities:
	- The last row is covered using horizontal tiles, leaving a floor of size `(i-1) × m`.
	- The last `m` rows are covered using vertical tiles in every column, leaving a floor of size `(i-m) × m`.
	This leads directly to the recurrence:
		dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-m]
	which gives an O(n) dynamic programming solution.
